Very little attention, however, has been paid to the widening gap between theory and practice, or to the ongoing disconnect between stated project goals and actual funded activities. Beyond Common Knowledge examines the standard methods of legal and judicial reform. Taking stock of international experience in legal and judicial reform in Latin America, Europe, India, and China, this volume answers key questions in the judicial reform debate: What are the common assumptions about the role of the courts in improving economic growth and democratic politics? Do we expect too much from the formal legal system? Is investing in judicial reform projects a good strategy for getting at the problems of governance that beset many developing countries? If not, what are we missing?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCourts. 0aJudicial process. 0aJustice, Administration of. 0aLaw reform. 0aRule of law. 4aLaw -- International and Comparative Law. 4aPolitics -- Comparative and International Politics. 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh1 aBlankenburg, Erhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Donald C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFix-Fierro, Héctor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFu, Hualing, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalanter, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález, Carlos Peña, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammergren, Linn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeller, Thomas C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeller, Thomas C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJensen, Erik G., econtributor.